jt-pve-storage-netapp (0.2.6-1) stable; urgency=high

  * Postinst Service Reload + Operator UX Release
  * Requirements: Proxmox VE 9.1 or later
  * Critical Fix - kpartx Partition Holders:
    - Fixed is_device_in_use() blocking ALL volume deletions on systems
      where the kernel auto-creates kpartx partition devices (e.g.
      <wwid>-part1, <wwid>-part2) on multipath LUNs. This happens on
      every VM disk with an OS installed (the guest's partition table is
      visible to the host kernel's partition scanner). Previously, these
      partition dm devices were treated as "real" holders and blocked
      free_image(). Now is_device_in_use() checks if ALL holders are
      bare kpartx partitions with no sub-holders (no LVM/dm-crypt on
      top). If so, they're safe to ignore - they are passive artifacts
      that will be removed during cleanup. Partitions with sub-holders
      (e.g. host LVM VG built on a partition) still correctly block.
    - Added kpartx -d cleanup step in cleanup_lun_devices() to explicitly
      remove partition devices before multipath flush.
    - Fixed get_device_usage_details() misinterpreting kpartx partition
      dm-names (e.g. "3600a...d33-part1") as LVM VG names.
  * Operator UX - Detailed is_device_in_use error messages:
    - free_image() now shows detailed diagnostics when a device cannot be
      deleted due to is_device_in_use() blocking. Previously showed generic
      "device is still in use (mounted, has holders, or open by process)".
      Now shows: exact holder device names and dm-names, auto-detected
      LVM VG name(s), root cause explanation (host LVM auto-activation of
      guest VGs, common on PVE 7->8->9 upgrades), exact fix commands
      (vgchange -an <vg>), and lvm.conf global_filter suggestion.
    - Added get_device_usage_details() helper in Multipath.pm that gathers
      holder names from /sys/block/<dev>/holders/, reads dm-name from sysfs,
      parses VG names from LVM dm-name conventions, and runs fuser -v for
      process details.
  * Orphan Cleanup Warning Cooldown:
    - Orphan detection warnings for untracked NETAPP multipath devices now
      use a 1-hour cooldown per WWID. Previously warned every 10 seconds
      (on every pvestatd poll), flooding the journal with identical messages.
      Cooldown state is stored in /var/run/pve-storage-netapp/ (tmpfs,
      cleared on reboot so warnings fire again after reboot).
  * Postinst - lvm.conf global_filter Detection:
    - Postinst now checks if /etc/lvm/lvm.conf global_filter excludes
      multipath device-mapper devices. If not, displays a prominent warning
      explaining that host-level LVM will auto-activate VGs found inside
      VM disks on plugin-managed LUNs, causing is_device_in_use() to block
      volume deletion. Shows recommended global_filter setting.
  * Postinst Fixes:
    - Added pvestatd to the service reload list. Previous versions only
      restarted pvedaemon and pveproxy, leaving pvestatd running with old
      plugin code in memory. pvestatd polls status() every 10 seconds;
      with old code it continued creating D-state children from the
      pre-v0.2.5 rescan_scsi_hosts() that wrote to non-iSCSI hosts.
      On the customer's HPE ProLiant, this caused permanent D-state
      accumulation even after v0.2.5 was installed, eventually triggering
      an iLO watchdog reboot. Now all three PVE services (pvedaemon,
      pvestatd, pveproxy) are reloaded.
    - Changed postinst from 'systemctl restart' to 'systemctl reload'
      (SIGHUP). PVE::Daemon handles SIGHUP by re-exec'ing itself,
      picking up new Perl modules without going through a stop phase.
      This avoids the bootstrapping problem where the OLD code has
      already created D-state children (unkillable by SIGKILL), and
      'systemctl restart' hangs waiting for them during stop. With
      reload, no stop phase is needed -- the running process re-execs
      in-place and D-state orphans are inherited by init.
    - If a service is not running at install time, postinst uses
      'systemctl start' instead of reload (reload requires active svc).
  * Background:
    Customer installed v0.2.5 on HPE ProLiant. pvedaemon and pveproxy
    were restarted with new code, but pvestatd was not touched. pvestatd
    continued running v0.2.4 code, calling the old rescan_scsi_hosts()
    every 10 seconds, creating new D-state children on host1 (smartpqi).
    Within minutes, 5 D-state processes accumulated (some lasting 4+
    hours). The system became unresponsive, HPE iLO hardware watchdog
    triggered a forced reboot. After reboot all services loaded v0.2.5
    from disk and the problem disappeared.

 -- Jason Cheng <jason@jason.tools>  Fri, 10 Apr 2026 15:00:00 +0800

jt-pve-storage-netapp (0.2.5-1) stable; urgency=critical

  * Non-iSCSI SCSI Host Scan Fix Release (CRITICAL)
  * Requirements: Proxmox VE 9.1 or later
  * Critical Bug Fix (production incident):
    - Fixed rescan_scsi_hosts() and FC.pm rescan_fc_hosts() iterating
      all entries in /sys/class/scsi_host/ and writing "- - -" to each
      host's scan file. This included non-iSCSI / non-FC hosts such as
      HBA RAID controllers, USB card readers, NVMe, virtio-scsi, etc.
      Writing to a non-iSCSI host's scan file triggers a driver-side
      full target rescan, which can hang for 600+ seconds inside some
      drivers. Observed in production on HPE ProLiant servers with the
      smartpqi driver (P408i-a controller): writes to host1/scan entered
      D-state for 10+ minutes in sas_user_scan, serializing every
      subsequent process that touched /sys/class/scsi_host/host1. This
      cascaded into:
        * pvedaemon workers unable to release VM config locks
          -> customer saw repeated "trying to acquire lock... got timeout"
        * pvestatd unable to complete status() polls
        * pvedaemon restart hanging indefinitely during postinst upgrade
        * VM operations (move-disk, resize, config update, boot change)
          intermittently hanging even on working-path storage
    - Fix: rescan_scsi_hosts() now sources the host list from
      /sys/class/iscsi_host/ (maintained by kernel scsi_transport_iscsi).
      Every iSCSI SCSI host registers there regardless of underlying
      driver (iscsi_tcp, iser, bnx2i, qla4xxx, qedi, be2iscsi, cxgb3i,
      cxgb4i, and any future iSCSI driver via iscsi_host_alloc()).
      Non-iSCSI hosts are categorically absent from that class, so
      iteration is both exhaustive and safe. Future-proof: new iSCSI
      drivers added to the kernel are picked up automatically without
      plugin code changes.
    - Fix: rescan_fc_hosts() in FC.pm had the same bug in its
      post-LIP SCSI scan loop. Now only iterates FC hosts from
      /sys/class/fc_host/ (already enumerated via get_fc_hosts()).
  * Background:
    A customer upgraded from v0.1.9 through v0.2.3 to v0.2.4 on a
    production HPE ProLiant server. After v0.2.3 the node hit
    "sysfs write to host1/scan timed out" warnings on every VM
    operation touching the plugin storage, leading to cascading VM
    lock timeouts and eventually pvedaemon restart hanging during
    v0.2.4 postinst upgrade. The previous releases had sysfs_write
    timeout protection (added in v0.2.0) which kept the parent
    process alive but left the D-state child child pinning the
    kernel scan lock for host1. The proper fix is to not write to
    host1 at all -- it is a hardware RAID controller, not an iSCSI
    target. This release finally addresses that architectural
    mistake that has existed since v0.1.0.

 -- Jason Cheng <jason@jason.tools>  Fri, 10 Apr 2026 12:00:00 +0800

jt-pve-storage-netapp (0.2.4-1) stable; urgency=high

  * Cleanup Path Hardening + Concurrency + Operator UX Release
  * Requirements: Proxmox VE 9.1 or later
  * Concurrency Fixes:
    - Fixed clone_image() disk-id TOCTOU race. The previous code did a
      volume_get pre-check to find a free disk ID, then called
      volume_clone() outside the loop. Two parallel clone_image() calls
      on the same VM (e.g. concurrent template clones from different
      cluster nodes, or any path that bypasses PVE's storage cfs lock)
      would both pass the pre-check with the same disk ID, race on
      volume_clone, and the loser would die with "already exists".
      Now volume_clone is inside the retry loop, and "already exists"
      errors trigger retry with the next disk ID. Same fix pattern as
      alloc_image v0.2.1 TOCTOU fix, applied to clone_image.
    - Fixed temporary FlexClone (snapshot read-access) TOCTOU race in
      _ensure_temp_clone(). Temp clone names are deterministic from
      volume+snap, so two parallel path() callers reading the same
      snapshot would race on volume_clone. Now treats "already exists"
      as success since the temp clone is shared and reusable.
  * Operator UX:
    - Added _translate_limit_error() helper that detects common ONTAP
      resource-limit errors (FlexVol cap, LUN cap, igroup LUN-map cap,
      aggregate full, SVM quota) and prepends operator-friendly
      one-line summaries explaining the cause and recovery action.
      Applied to all alloc_image and clone_image die sites. Operators
      now see "ONTAP FlexVol limit reached on this SVM/node" instead
      of raw "POST /api/storage/volumes failed: 917927: Maximum number
      of volumes is reached on Vserver svm0".
  * Bug Fixes (production audit):
    - Fixed clone_image() cleanup path missing lun_unmap_all() before
      volume_delete() on failure. Same bug pattern previously fixed in
      alloc_image() in v0.2.1, but the equivalent fix was missed in
      clone_image(). When lun_map() failed partway through (e.g. mapped
      to some node igroups but failed on others in per-node mode),
      cleanup attempted volume_delete on a still-mapped LUN. ONTAP
      rejects this, leaving orphaned igroup mappings and ghost LUNs
      visible to other cluster nodes -- which then become stale devices
      that can hang processes touching them.
    - Added pre-snapshot host-side buffer flush in volume_snapshot().
      For running VMs qemu's freeze handles consistency, but for
      offline volumes or external script callers, dirty page cache was
      not flushed before snapshot_create, potentially producing
      filesystem-inconsistent snapshots. Skips flush if device is in
      use by another process (live migration safety).
    - Removed dead code: get_multipath_wwid() in Multipath.pm. The
      function was exported but had zero callers across the codebase
      and used basename() without symlink resolution -- a latent
      footgun for any future caller that passed /dev/mapper/<wwid>.
      Safer to delete than to leave as a trap.

 -- Jason Cheng <jason@jason.tools>  Thu, 09 Apr 2026 12:00:00 +0800

jt-pve-storage-netapp (0.2.3-1) stable; urgency=critical

  * Pre-Upgrade Stale Device Handling Release
  * Requirements: Proxmox VE 9.1 or later
  * Critical Fixes for Production Upgrade Scenarios:
    - Fixed orphan cleanup not handling pre-upgrade stale multipath devices.
      Previous v0.2.2 behavior only cleaned WWIDs that path() was called on
      AFTER upgrade. Stale devices left over from earlier plugin versions
      (v0.1.x) were never tracked and could not be cleaned automatically.
      v0.2.3 now auto-imports current ONTAP pve_* LUN WWIDs into the tracking
      file on every status() poll, ensuring all cluster nodes converge to a
      consistent view regardless of when path() was last called locally.
  * Multipath Hang Prevention (CRITICAL):
    - Fixed cleanup_lun_devices() hanging on multipath devices with
      queue_if_no_path enabled. Now disables queueing via 'multipathd
      disablequeueing map' and 'dmsetup message ... fail_if_no_path'
      BEFORE attempting any sync/flush, so I/O fails fast instead of
      queueing forever.
    - Added timeout (10s) to all multipath_flush() and multipath_reload()
      operations.
    - Fallback to 'dmsetup remove --force --retry' if 'multipath -f' times
      out, bypassing the multipath flush logic that hangs on dead devices.
    - Added timeout (10s) to 'multipathd remove map' calls.
  * Postinst Stale Device Detection:
    - Postinst now scans for NETAPP multipath devices with all paths failed
      and displays a prominent warning listing the WWIDs and exact commands
      to clean them. Does NOT auto-clean to avoid touching manually-managed
      storage. Especially important when upgrading from v0.1.x or v0.2.0/1
      which left orphans without tracking them.
  * Critical Symlink Resolution Fix (DATA LOSS PREVENTION):
    - Added _resolve_block_device_name() helper that resolves /dev/mapper/<wwid>
      symlinks to the underlying dm-N kernel name. Required for any /sys/block/
      access on multipath device paths.
    - Fixed is_device_in_use() to use the helper. Previously, calling
      is_device_in_use('/dev/mapper/<wwid>') would do basename() to get the
      WWID, then look in /sys/block/<wwid>/holders/ which doesn't exist.
      Result: LVM and other holders on multipath devices were silently missed,
      and free_image() would happily delete in-use volumes -- DATA LOSS RISK.
      This affects any environment with LVM/dm-crypt/etc on top of NetApp
      multipath devices (a common production setup).
    - Fixed get_multipath_slaves() to use the helper. Previously the slave
      list was empty for /dev/mapper/<wwid> paths, breaking volume_resize
      and any other operation that needed to enumerate paths.
  * Snapshot Rollback Fix:
    - volume_snapshot_rollback() now uses per-device rescan instead of
      host scan, and adds post-rollback kernel buffer cache invalidation.
      Without cache invalidation, reads after rollback could return stale
      cached data from before the rollback.
  * Critical Resize Fix:
    - Fixed volume_resize() using rescan_scsi_hosts() (host scan) instead of
      per-device rescan. Host scan is for discovering NEW devices and does
      NOT trigger re-reading the size of existing devices. Result: after
      resizing the LUN on ONTAP, the kernel still saw the old size and
      QEMU's block_resize would fail with "Cannot grow device files".
      Additionally, host scan can hang on unresponsive iSCSI hosts (the
      sysfs_write_with_timeout protected the parent but the rescan never
      completed).
    - volume_resize() now correctly:
      1. Iterates over the multipath device's SCSI slaves
      2. Calls `echo 1 > /sys/block/sdX/device/rescan` on each (with timeout)
      3. Calls `multipathd resize map <name>` to refresh multipath size
    - This is the correct sequence for kernel + multipath to see the new
      LUN size after a backend resize.
  * Slow Operation Support:
    - volume_delete() now uses an extended 60s API timeout (was 15s).
      FlexClone deletion can take 30+ seconds on ONTAP, especially when
      cleaning up snapshot dependencies. The 15s default caused spurious
      "command timed out" warnings even though the operation eventually
      succeeded via the retry loop.
    - _request() now supports per-call timeout override.
  * Background:
    Customer environment hit a node hang during disk migration when 'vgs'
    scanned a stale multipath device that had queue_if_no_path enabled.
    The stale device was left over from earlier plugin versions and was
    never tracked by v0.2.2's orphan cleanup mechanism. Result: vgs entered
    D state, pvedaemon hung waiting for it, and 'systemctl restart' also
    hung. Recovery required reboot. v0.2.3 prevents this by:
      1. Auto-importing alive WWIDs so cluster nodes know about ALL LUNs
      2. Disabling queue_if_no_path before any cleanup operation
      3. Warning at install time about pre-existing stale devices

